    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n^2 x^n}{(n+3)!}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{n^2}{(n+3)!}}{\frac{(n+1)^2}{(n+4)!}}
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+4)! n^2}{(n+3)! (n+1)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+4)n^2}{(n+1)^2} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{n^3 + 4n^2}{n^2 + 2n + 1} = \infty
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The asymptotic order of the numerator is greater than the
          denominator, so the limit is <m>\infty</m>. The radius of
          convergence is <m>\infty</m>, which means that the power
          series converges for all real numbers. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{\sqrt{n}(x-2)^n}{n!}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{\sqrt{n}}{n!}}{\frac{\sqrt{n+1}}{(n+1)!}}
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+1)! \sqrt{n}}{n! \sqrt{n+1}} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(n+1)\sqrt{n}}{\sqrt{n+1}} = \infty 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The numerator has a higher asymptotic order, so the limit is
          <m>\infty</m>. The radius of convergence is <m>\infty</m>,
          meaning that the power series converges for all real
          numbers. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n!x^n}{(2n)!}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{n!}{(2n!}}{\frac{(n+1)!}{(2n+2)!}} 
              \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{n! (2n+2)!}{(n+1)! (2n)!}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{(2n+2)(2n+1)}{n+1)} = \infty 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The numerator has higher asymptotic order, so the limit is
          <m>\infty</m>. The radius of convergence is <m>\infty</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the radius of convergence of this power series.
          <me>
            \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(x-3)^n}{n + \cos (pi n)} 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We use the limit form for calculating radius of convergence.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              R \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{c_n}{c_{n+1}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left|
              \frac{\frac{1}{n+\cos (\pi
              n)}{\frac{1}{n+1+\cos(\pi(n+1))}} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} 
              \frac{n + 1 + \cos(\pi(n+1))}{n + \cos (\pi n)} = 1
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Both denominator and numerator have the same asymptotic
          order and the leading coefficients are both 1, so the limit
          is 1. (Note that the cosine term, since it doesn't grow at
          all, has no effect on the asymptotic order.) The radius of
          convergence is 1.
        </p>
      </solution>
